                            NEWT'S ETHICS PROBLEMS:
                          THE BEN JONES FEC COMPLAINT



Overview

   On September 22, 1994, former Congressman Ben Jones - then opposing
   Newt for Georgia's 6th District House seat - filed a complaint with
   the Federal Election Commission against GOPAC, the PAC Newt controls.
   Jones alleged that GOPAC had been funding federal campaigns with
   corporate contributions in clear violation of federal law.

   Jones referenced a recently-released GOPAC fundraising letter
   requesting contributions to help Republicans gain control of the U.S.
   House. At the same time, GOPAC was allegedly insisting to the FEC that
   only 0.1% of its budget involved funding for federal candidates.


The NewtWatch Recap

   Laws Allegedly Violated:
     * 2 U.S.C. sections 431 et seq.
     * 11 C.F.R. 100.1 et seq.

   Best Fightin' Words:
     * Jones's letter alleges: "GOPAC has cleverly engineered a
       complicated scheme to avoid full disclosure and compliance with
       federal and state election laws."

   Newt's Reaction:
     * Newt was generally dismissive of Jones and others charges, telling
       Roll Call (February 16, 1995) "For the moment, my defeated
       opponent, various embittered Democrats, various folks that
       ideologically disagree with me, have each come up with spurious
       charges."
     * Newt's Congressional spokesman, Tony Blankley, has also dismissed
       Jones as "feasting on a banquet of sour grapes" (The Washington
       Post, January 27, 1995).




                            NEWT'S ETHICS PROBLEMS:
              THE CONGRESSIONAL ACCOUNTABILITY PROJECT COMPLAINT


Overview

   On February 6, 1995, the Congressional Accountability Project - a
   good-government watchdog organization affiliated with Ralph Nader -
   filed a complaint against Newt with the House Ethics Committee
   alleging possible violations of federal law and House ethics rules
   regarding the official role played by Newt's principal advisor, Joseph
   Gaylord.

   Gaylord has been described as Newt's "super-chief of staff." He is
   reportedly a regular attendee at Congressional meetings, and has been
   instrumental in choosing, directing and setting payroll for Newt's
   Congressional staff. According to one report, he has even scouted
   Capitol offices for furniture for Newt's office.

   In actuality, Gaylord hasn't done anything one wouldn't expect a House
   Speaker's chief of staff to do. The problem is, Gaylord isn't Newt's
   chief of staff. He is neither on the Congressional payroll nor
   accountable to American taxpayers. Gaylord is a consultant to GOPAC,
   the political action committee Newt controls.


The NewtWatch Recap

  LAWS AND RULES ALLEGEDLY VIOLATED:
     * 2 U.S.C. 59e(d)
     * 31 U.S.C. 1342
     * House Rule 45, Cl. 2

  BEST FIGHTIN' WORDS:
     * Right at the top, the letter reads: "Request for Investigation of
       Speaker Newt Gingrich for Possible Violation of Federal Law and
       House Ethics Rules."


  NEWT'S REACTION:
     * Newt-spokesman Tony Blankley described Gaylord as "an outside
       consultant, who provides political advice, which the rules of the
       House permit. He comes here from time to time to give consultative
       advice" (The Washington Post, February 8, 1995).


